  "sections": [
    {
      "id": "about",
      "title": "About",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "What Is GitHub Fabric?",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "GitHub Fabric starts with a stubbornly simple premise: GitHub isn\u2019t only a place to store code \u2014 it can be the place code <em>becomes</em> a system. Not \u201cCI for a repo,\u201d but <strong>repos as first-class, runnable infrastructure units</strong>."
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "In a Fabric you don\u2019t just <em>reference</em> upstream projects. You <strong>ingest them</strong>, <strong>splice in curated changes</strong>, and <strong>run them</strong> \u2014 reliably, repeatedly, and by name \u2014 on top of GitHub Actions."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "architecture",
      "title": "Architecture \u2014 The Three Planes",
      "grid": "grid-3",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "1 \u00b7 Source Plane",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Faithful capture of upstream repos. Track origin + commit SHA; keep raw imports segregated from runtime material. The source plane is for <em>truth</em>, not convenience."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "2 \u00b7 Transformation Plane",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Cull bulk, patch configs, normalize entry-points, and wrap modules with an adapter contract \u2014 turning heterogeneous repos into consistent, driveable units."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "3 \u00b7 Execution Plane",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "GitHub Actions is the runtime substrate: scheduled syncs, workflow-dispatch runs by name, contract tests, artifact provenance, caching, and isolation."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "dna",
      "title": "Upstream DNA",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "Repos as Genetic Material",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Most platforms treat upstream code like a dependency. GitHub Fabric treats it like <strong>genetic material</strong> \u2014 something you import, normalize, and express under controlled conditions."
            },
            {
              "type": "list",
              "items": [
                "Taking in source from one or many upstream repos",
                "Splicing targeted edits \u2014 policy, structure, configs, adapters",
                "Expressing a runnable form via a standardized entry-point",
                "Preserving provenance \u2014 exact upstream commit, applied patches, and outputs"
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "lifecycle",
      "title": "Workflow Lifecycle",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "Resolve \u2192 Materialize \u2192 Validate \u2192 Execute \u2192 Emit",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "lifecycle",
              "steps": ["Resolve", "Materialize", "Validate", "Execute", "Emit"]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Every run converts a module name into a spec, fetches upstream, applies cull + patch rules, stamps provenance, runs contract tests, executes with constrained permissions, and publishes artifacts."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "addressability",
      "title": "Name Addressability",
      "grid": "grid-2",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "Modules",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Module names map to runnable capability. Trigger <code>run &lt;name&gt;</code> and the Fabric resolves code, rules, environment, and workflow \u2014 then executes."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Templates",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Template names map to scaffolded new repos. The Fabric becomes a production line: standard workflows, sane defaults, consistent structure."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "strengths",
      "title": "Why It Matters",
      "grid": "grid-2",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "Curated Distribution",
          "content": [
            { "type": "paragraph", "html": "Scattered capability becomes a shelf of approved, runnable modules." }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Reviewable Upgrades",
          "content": [
            { "type": "paragraph", "html": "Upstream changes arrive as PRs with diffs, test results, and pinned SHAs." }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Reproducibility by Design",
          "content": [
            { "type": "paragraph", "html": "Runs are tied to exact inputs and versions. \u201cIt broke\u201d is always traceable." }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Unified Governance",
          "content": [
            { "type": "paragraph", "html": "Approvals, policies, audit trails, and secrets management live where the work executes." }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
